hands_on_practices.problem:
A two-dimensional Digital Image Correlation (DIC) analysis tracks a square image subset whose center is chosen as the spatial origin at coordinates $(x,y)=(0,0)$. The deformed configuration is modeled by an affine warp in a forward-additive parameterization with parameter vector $\mathbf{p}=(p_{1},p_{2},p_{3},p_{4},p_{5},p_{6})^{\mathsf{T}}$ defined through
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
x' \\
y'
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{pmatrix}
+
\begin{pmatrix}
p_{1} \\
p_{4}
\end{pmatrix}
+
\begin{pmatrix}
p_{2} & p_{3} \\
p_{5} & p_{6}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{pmatrix},
$$
so that $x'=x+p_{1}+p_{2}x+p_{3}y$ and $y'=y+p_{4}+p_{5}x+p_{6}y$. The material undergoes a rigid-body rotation by an angle $\theta$ about the subset center, with no translation and no strain. Angles are expressed in radians.

Starting only from (i) the rigid-body kinematic mapping for a planar rotation by angle $\theta$ about the origin and (ii) the affine warp definition given above, derive the equivalent affine parameter vector $\mathbf{p}(\theta)$ that exactly represents this rotation in the forward-additive parameterization. Next, consider a forward-additive Gauss–Newton (GN) iteration that updates $\mathbf{p}\leftarrow \mathbf{p}+\Delta\mathbf{p}$ when the true motion is an additional small rotation $\delta\theta$ about the same center. Derive, to first order in $\delta\theta$, the dependence of the increments $\Delta p_{2},\Delta p_{3},\Delta p_{5},\Delta p_{6}$ on the current angle $\theta$ and the increment $\delta\theta$, and interpret in one sentence what this implies about parameter coupling under forward-additive GN updates.

Provide, as your final answer, only the closed-form expression for the affine parameter vector $\mathbf{p}(\theta)$ as a $1\times 6$ row vector. No rounding is required.
